Maybe you can get started by telling us a bit about your background and how you got interested
in bioelectricity in the first place. Sure, yeah, my background, I started out in physics
and I got my bachelor's degree in physics and then went to graduate school at Purdue.
And in the physics department, they had professors give us a lecture about their work.
It was a rotating thing, so we'd be able to hear all the professors what they're up to and
decide if we want to work with them. And one of the professors they came on to do that was Lionel
Jaffe. And he was actually in the Department of Biological Sciences, but he liked to go to the
physics department because he found the students there were better and more appropriate for his
interests. He told us about his work in measuring electrical currents in germinating seaweed eggs.
And I found that fascinating. At that point, I had never taken any biology in my career.
And to think that you can actually measure currents in living cells, I thought was fascinating.
So I went and did a rotation with him, fell in love with the whole idea of measuring
these currents and I did my PhD under his guidance. And that really was a turning point in my life
because instead of studying solids and solid state physics, I was studying living cells
and we're measuring currents in those cells. It was actually fascinating. So we developed a
whole new technique which we called at the time we called the vibrating probe. It was basically
an electrode that vibrated back and forth and we used a lock and amplifier to measure the voltage
between the two points. And if current is flowing in a medium, that will generate a voltage in the
medium and it's very small because you're in seawater. It's very conductive. So the voltage
you generate is really in the nano volt, 10 to the minus ninth volt range, very small. But with
some fancy electronics and averaging many, many measurements, you can get down into those regions
and we did. We measured currents around the single fucoid egg, a pelvicia egg, and that's how I got
into it. It was ever since then, I've been looking at those kinds of things, fields and currents,
in cells and their response to imposed fields because that's so critical for development
of our organisms. So it's really been a fun. So when you first got into this research, you
