Not really. Bioelectric was a term that was coined much later. There it was simply called
ionic currents in development. We had a whole book that we wrote called Ionic Currents in Development
and that was about, we just referred to it. See, when people talked about currents,
they thought about electron movement in wires. And, you know, of course, we aren't talking about
that. We're talking about sodium, potassium, chloride movements through cells. So that's why
we emphasize the ionic current aspect because that's a whole new way of thinking of current
with ions carrying it. And, yeah, that's the whole way we started describing it. And it was
kind of new. I think it was fairly new. People didn't quite know what to make of it at the time
because of, you know, they didn't think of cells as driving currents through themselves. It was a
